{{About|castle in Osmaniye Province|castle in Muğla Province|Bodrum Castle}} [[File:Bodrumkale, Osmaniye Province, Turkey.jpg|thumb|Bodrumkale in Osmaniye Province, Turkey]]
'''Bodrumkale''' is a castle ruin in [[Osmaniye Province]], [[Turkey]]. It is situated on a hill at {{coord|37|10|39|N|36|11|15|E}}. Its distance to [[Osmaniye]] is about {{convert|12|km}}. The castle is to the northeast of the ancient city of [[Castabala (city)|Castabala]]. In medieval times it controlled the road from [[Central Anatolia]] to the [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]] coast. In 1987 an archaeological assessment and accurate plan were published.<ref name="edwards">{{cite book|last1=Edwards|first1=Robert W.| title=The Fortifications of Armenian Cilicia: Dumbarton Oaks Studies XXIII | date=1987|publisher=Dumbarton Oaks, Trustees for Harvard University| location=Washington, D.C.|isbn=0-88402-163-7|pages=92–95, 282, pls.291a–291c}}</ref> The castle is divided into two baileys or wards and has six towers. Most of its masonry was cut directly from the limestone outcrop and not plundered from the ancient city below. The lower level of the south tower functioned as a cistern.
It is dated to 13th century <ref>[http://www.osmaniye.gov.tr/kastabala-antik-kenti Osmaniye governor's page {{tr icon}}]</ref> during the [[Armenian Kingdom of Cilicia]]. When the castle was captured by the [[Ramadanids]] in the next century, it was already abandoned.<ref name="G">[http://www.ben1gezginim.com/yer_tanitimlari/osmaniye/bodrum-kalesi-kastabala-hierapolis-sehri-osmaniye.html Travellers' page {{tr icon}}]</ref>
