{{Infobox artwork | image_file=Three of the Players - John Brack (1953).jpg | backcolor=#FBF5DF | painting_alignment=right | image_size=300px | title=Three of the Players | artist=[[John Brack]] | year=[[1953 in art|1953]] | medium=oil on canvas | height_metric=38.5 | width_metric=84.0 | height_imperial= | width_imperial= | metric_unit=cm | imperial_unit=in | city= | museum=Private collection | url= }} '''''Three of the Players''''' is a [[1953 in art|1953]] painting by Australian artist [[John Brack]]. The painting depicts three [[Australian rules football]]ers from the [[Collingwood Football Club]].<ref name="Green">{{cite news|last1=Green|first1=Warwick|title=Retrogram pic special: Footy stars as works of art|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/afl/retrogram-pic-special-footy-stars-as-works-of-art/story-fni5f22o-1226878126454|accessdate=24 May 2016|work=Herald Sun|publisher=News Limited|date=8 April 2014}}</ref> The players are thought by some to be [[Lou Richards]], [[Jack Regan]] and [[Phonse Kyne]]. However, Brack's widow, Helen, was of the opinion that they are not recognisable individuals but "stereotyped characters".<ref name="Boland">{{cite news|last1=Boland|first1=Michaela|title=Collingwood opts to pass up on painting|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/national-affairs/collingwood-opts-to-pass-up-on-painting/story-fn59niix-1225909100311|accessdate=24 May 2016|work=The Australian|publisher=News Limited|date=24 August 2010}}</ref>
The painting has been described as "Brack's unique comment on canvas observing the deeper but universal emotions of Australian Rules Football the national game".<ref name="AuctionCatalogue">{{cite web|last1=Thomas|first1=David|title=John Brack (1920 - 1999) Three of the Players, 1953|url=http://www.deutscherandhackett.com/auction/16-important-australian-international-fine-art/lot/three-players-1953|website=Important Australian and International Fine Art Sydney 1 September 2010|publisher=Deutscher and Hackett|accessdate=24 May 2016}}</ref> The work has also been described as the "most significant sport painting by Brack and the most significant artwork to depict the [Collingwood Football Club]."<ref name="Boland" />
{{quote|Seeking verities beyond the everyday suburban fringe, Brack wittily likens the three Collingwood football personalities in their black and white striped jumpers to three types of players as present in the ages of man. The bulk of youth looks observantly to the older player, eye-lined with experience, while dogged determination is captured in the maturity of the manly profile.|Deutscher and Hackett|<ref name="AuctionCatalogue" />}}
First exhibited in the [[Peter Bray Gallery]] in 1953, for more than 40 years the painting hung in the [[South Yarra]] home of Australian architect [[Robin Boyd (architect)|Robin Boyd]].<ref name="AuctionCatalogue" /> In 2010, it sold for [[Australian dollar|AUD]]900,000 to a private collector.<ref name="Sale">{{cite news|title=Collingwood painting sells for $900,000|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2010-09-01/collingwood-painting-sells-for-900000/966498|accessdate=24 May 2016|work=ABC News|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|date=2 September 2010}}</ref>
